Bearer + --workspace flags + workspace-routing fallback + project re-resolve.

Adds the genuinely-upstreamable subset of opencode-bearer-auth changes.
This patch is independent of any deployment glue and is intended to be
proposed upstream once the API stabilises.

What this adds:
  - `OPENCODE_SERVER_BEARER` env (core/flag/flag.ts) and a Bearer
    response from `ServerAuth.header()` (server/auth.ts). The bearer
    can also be passed via `opencode attach --bearer`.
  - `opencode attach --workspace <id>` propagates through `tui()` into
    `SDKProvider` (passed as `experimental_workspaceID`) and into
    `ProjectProvider` (which seeds the workspace into the project store
    so downstream components -- including `WorkspaceProvider`, which
    reads `store.workspace.current` -- target the chosen workspace).
    Net effect: the TUI's home prompt opens new sessions against the
    workspace named on the command line.
  - `validateSession` honours the workspace argument.
  - Workspace-routing middleware reads `x-opencode-workspace` for ALL
    methods, not just GET/HEAD. The SDK only rewrites header->query
    for GET/HEAD, leaving POST/PUT/DELETE with the header verbatim;
    upstream's server used to ignore the header on those methods.
  - Post-`adapter.create` project re-resolve in `Workspace.create`.
    Upstream copies the requesting instance's `project.id` at row
    insert time; for an unscoped `POST /experimental/workspace` that
    resolves to the front-opencode's cwd-based project (typically
    `global` for a non-git cwd), and every workspace ends up sharing
    `project_id = global`. Cascades into broken session lists,
    broken SPA "review changes" widget, and broken workspace-scoped
    `--continue`. This hunk runs `Project.fromDirectory(info.directory)`
    after `WorkspaceAdapterRuntime.create` resolves and UPDATEs the
    workspace row's `project_id` to the git-root OID.

Server-side opencode does NOT validate the Bearer -- this patch only
adds the surface area for clients to send it. Deployments fronting
opencode with a JWT-validating reverse proxy can use this; deployments
without a proxy continue to use HTTP Basic via `--password`.

